      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Are they significantly different?\n\n**pKa₁ (carboxyl group): No difference at all.**\nBoth glycine and alanine have pKa₁ = **2.33** under identical conditions. The carboxyl group is essentially unaffected by the methyl substituent on the α-carbon.\n\n**pKa₂ (ammonium group): Small but real difference.**\nAlanine's amino pKa₂ (**9.71**) is **0.14 units higher** than glycine's (**9.57**). This is a modest but chemically meaningful difference — the methyl group in alanine is slightly electron-donating, making the –NH₃⁺ group marginally harder to deprotonate (i.e., the amine is a slightly stronger base). A 0.14-unit difference corresponds to alanine's –NH₂ being about **38% more basic** than glycine's at equilibrium (10^0.14 ≈ 1.38).",
